  "prompt": "How can Sanskrit, the so-called mother of all languages, be a dead language today?",
  "response": "There are a few important points to clarify about Sanskrit:\n\n1. Living vs. Dead Language Status\n- Sanskrit is technically a \"classical\" language, not completely dead\n- It's still used in religious and ceremonial contexts\n- Some communities in India still speak Sanskrit, though not as a primary language\n\n2. Historical Significance\n- Sanskrit is considered the classical language of Hinduism and Buddhism\n- It's an important liturgical language in Hinduism, similar to Latin in Catholicism\n- Many Indian classical texts and scriptures are written in Sanskrit\n\n3. Linguistic Influence\n- While not \"mother of all languages\" literally, Sanskrit significantly influenced many Indo-Aryan languages\n- It's part of the Indo-European language family\n- Has substantial impact on languages like Hindi, Marathi, Bengali\n\n4. Contemporary Usage\n- Some schools in India teach Sanskrit\n- Used in academic and scholarly research\n- Some institutions and communities still actively use it\n- Small communities in India still speak Sanskrit as a primary language\n\n5. Academic Recognition\n- Recognized as an official language in one Indian state (Uttarakhand)\n- Continues to be studied in linguistic and cultural research\n\nSo while not widely spoken, Sanskrit is not entirely \"dead\" but exists in a specialized, preserved form.",
